Dollar

Reading and regulating the format of the dollar data and controlling the data types:

dolar <- read_excel("dolar.xlsx")
names(dolar) = c("date", "dolar_value")
dolar <- as.data.table(dolar[2:2945,1:2])
dolar$date <- format(as.Date(dolar$date, format = "%d/%m/%Y"), "%Y-%m-%d")

The data types are correct. Plotting dollar rates and the fitting line:

ggplot(dolar, aes(x=date, y=dolar_value)) +
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("") + scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%m/%y") + stat_smooth() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 18)) +  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) +
    xlab("Date") + ylab("Dollar Rate") + theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size = 25)) + theme(axis.title.y=element_text(size = 25)) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

We can examine the dollar data:

Overall we can see an increasing trend in dollar rates and the increase is sharpening in the last two years as we can see from the fitting line.

There is no observable monthly or quarterly effect as dollar exchange rates does not depend on season or the month but depends on the economic decisions and policies on both side government. However, we observe a trend on the extreme points of the graph.

The first abnormality on 09.18 which is the date when the president of TCMB is changed suddenly and it creates an insecure enviroment for Turkish currency. Another abnormability is again happening when the president of TCMB is changed. We can drive the conclusion that unexpected changes in the president of TCMB cause dramatic rises in dollar rates.

The Correlation between Euro and Dollar

euro_dolar <- dolar[,Euro:=euro$euro_value]
cor(euro_dolar$Euro , euro_dolar$dolar_value,  method = "pearson", use = "complete.obs")
## [1] 0.9937468

The correllation is positive and it is extremely high as we expected. Plotting to understand the relationship better:

par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
ggplot(euro_dolar, aes(x=dolar_value, y=Euro)) +
  geom_point() + 
  xlab("") 

ggplot(euro_dolar, aes(x=date)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = Euro), color = "red") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = dolar_value), color="blue")

On these graphs, we can see euro dolar movements in a similar way. In the scatter plot, the slope is almost constant with minor deviations. In the second graph their parallel motions can be seen easily.

Correlation and Impact Analysis

As we can see from the graph, we expect high correlation between two data.

konut_ihtiyac <- konut[,ihtiyac:=ihtiyac$ihtiyac_index]
cor(konut_ihtiyac$konut, konut_ihtiyac$ihtiyac, method = "pearson", use = "complete.obs")
## [1] 0.9432285

As expected the correlation is positive and exteremly high.

Next, we will try to answer the question whether we can explain interest rates and currency rates by comparing their time series. First we need to scale the dollar rates and add a secondary axis to make a meaningful interpretation.

Regulation the data and plotting:

dolar_haftalik <- read_excel("dolar_haftalik.xlsx")
## New names:
## * `` -> ...3
dolar_haftalik <- dolar_haftalik[1:588,1:2]
konut_ihtiyac <- konut[,dolar:=dolar_haftalik[,2]]
konut_ihtiyac$dolar <- as.numeric(konut_ihtiyac$dolar)*4

ggplot(konut_ihtiyac, aes(x=date)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = konut), color = "red") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = ihtiyac), color="blue") + geom_line(aes(y = dolar), color = "black")+
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Interest Rates",
    sec.axis = sec_axis( trans=~.*0.25, name="Dollar Rates") 
  ) + scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%m/%y") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 15)) +  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) +
    xlab("Date") + ylab("Consumer Loan") + theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size = 25)) + theme(axis.title.y=element_text(size = 25))

On this graph we can see that right after the rise in 2018, interest rates are increased. This justifies our theory. Also, we can say that wen the interest rates are lowered dollar rates kept increasing. For example in 09/16 we can see after the loan interest lowered dollar rates increased.
